1a.

It is always a good idea to visually inspect a source of data before you start analyzing it in R. According to the figure above, what is the least and most number of social events that any woman participated in? Which women were most active (i.e. participated in the most events)?

By counting the number of ’X’s in the each row, we can determine that Mrs. Evelyn Jefferson, Miss Laura Mandeville, and Mrs. Nora Fayette were the most active, each attending 8 of the 14 events. Several women were much less active, attending as few as 2 events.

1b.

Is there anything you can tell informally about the social structure among these women just by looking at the events table? Do you think the women are separated into different cliques? Do you think some of the people might be more central to the social life than others?

While it’s hard to say anything substatial, it does look like there are two major “clusters” of women who tended to participate in the same events. Moreover, there are clearly some women who participate in many more evens than others, suggesting they may be more central to the social scene.

1d.

Now that the table is represented in the matrix events, we can use R to tell us a bit more about it. The functions rowSums(events) and colSums(events) will add up all of the numbers in each row and in each column of events, respectively. Using these functions, answer the following questions (show your code for each):

  • Which event was the most popular (had the most attendees)?
  • How many women attended exactly four events? To find the most-attended event, you can examine the column sums directly:
colSums(events)
##  [1]  3  3  6  4  8  8 10 14 12  6  4  7  4  4

The 8th event in the list is the largest in the list, with 14 women attending. You can also ask R to tell you which value is the maximum in a vector: To find the most-attended event, you can examine the column sums directly:

event_participation <- colSums(events)
which.max(event_participation)
## [1] 8

To find how many events were attended by exactly, you can examine the row sums directly:

rowSums(events)
##  [1] 8 7 8 7 4 4 4 3 4 4 4 6 7 8 7 4 2 2

From this you can count that seven of the women attended exactly 4 events. But you can also have R do this counting for you:

person_participation <- rowSums(events)
# create a vector with TRUE for women who attended exactly four events:
attended_four <- person_participation==4
attended_four
##  [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE
## [13] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
# when you take the `sum()` of a TRUE/FALSE vector, it simply counts the 
# number of TRUE values:
sum(attended_four)
## [1] 7

2a.

Fortunately for us, there is a very basic technique from linear algebra that will turn an affiliation matrix like the one you created above into a co-occurrence matrix that will measure co-attendance at events. To do so, we will use matrix multiplication. You don’t need to know anything about linear algebra for this to work, and for the time being, you can just treat it like a magic wand (we will cover this more in a later class).

co_attend <- events %*% t(events)

2b.

Visually inspect this new matrix co_attend, either by typing it into the R console on its own or by clicking on it in the RStudio “environment” pane.

  • How many rows and columns does it have?

co_attend had 18 rows and 18 columns

dim(co_attend)
## [1] 18 18
  • What number is in the third row of the first column, and what does it represent in plain language?

The number in the third row of the first column represents the number of events that Miss Theresa Anderson attended with Mrs. Evelyn Jefferson:

co_attend[3,1]
## [1] 7
  • What number is in the last row of the last column, and what does it represent in plain language?

The number in the last row of the last column represents the total number of events that Mrs. Flora Price attended:

co_attend[18,18]
## [1] 2
  • Where would you look in this matrix to tell how many events Mrs. Flora Price co-attended with Miss Laura Mandeville?

To find that out, you could look either in the last row of the second column (co_attend[18,2]) or the second row of the last column (co_attend[2,18]). The value is 0.

2c.

Use the max() and min() functions to determine the maximum and minimum number of events that any pair of women in this sample attended together. Note: this question was harder than I intended! To get the right answer you need to exclude the diagonal of the matrix. One way to do do this is to look only at the ‘upper triangular’ part of the matrix:

# get the values from just the upper triangular part
co_attend_utri <- co_attend[upper.tri(co_attend)]
# print it

2d.

Make a new matrix, called co_attend_3plus that has the same shape as co_attend, but whose values are either TRUE or FALSE, indicating for each pair of women whether they have attended at least 3 event together. (Note: This one may be a little tricky for new R users. The operator >= will tell you whether the value on the left is at least as big as the value on the right.)

co_attend_3plus <- co_attend >= 3
  • How does co_attend_3plus represent a different type of relationship between the pairs of women than co_attend?

co_attend represents the number of events each pair of women attendended together. This represents a relation of social connection that ranges from non-existent (0) to weak (1) to strong (7). In contrast, co_attend_3plus represents a binary (0/1) relation of relatively strong social connections.

3a.

The function graph_from_adjacency_matrix() from the igraph package converts an adjacency matrix like the co-attendance matrix you created above into a graph object. It automatically figures out how many nodes there are in the network by looking at the number of rows/columns in the matrix, and constructs edges between those nodes based on the data. Use the following command to created an undirected, weighted network from the co_attend matrix you already made:

library(igraph)
## 
## Attaching package: 'igraph'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     decompose, spectrum
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     union
event_net <- graph_from_adjacency_matrix(
  co_attend, mode='undirected', 
  weighted=TRUE, diag=FALSE)

3b.

We will talk about plotting networks in detail later in the course, but for the moment we can mostly use the default options built into igraph. Use the following two commands to (a) tell igraph that we want the weight of the edges to be reflected in the width of the lines in the plot, and (b) to plot event_net using the default parameters. Don’t worry about how these commands work yet.

E(event_net)$width <- E(event_net)$weight
plot(event_net)

3c.

Look at the plot that is created. What kinds of patterns can you see? Who is central and who is peripheral to the social structure this network represents?

This is a tightly connected network. Some women seem central to the network (e.g. Miss Ruth DeSand, labeled 9 in the graph), while others have only a peripheral attachment (e.g. number 18, Miss Flora Price, who only has week connections to the other nodes).

3d.

We are now going to create and plot an unweighted network from the matrix co_attend_3plus you created earlier based on a different measure of “relationship” between the women.

event_net_3plus <- graph_from_adjacency_matrix(
 co_attend_3plus, mode='undirected', diag=FALSE)
plot(event_net_3plus)

Execute the commands above and inspect this new network visually, then answer the following questions:

  • What is different about this network?

This network is much sparser. It also seems to show more obvious structure, with two small ‘clusters’. Moreover, there are now isolated nodes (17 and 18) that are not connected to anyone else in the network.

  • Why does it look so different?

By removing the weakest relations, the network shows only ties that represent a relatively strong link between the women. This means that we are hiding the co-attendance patters than might be incidental or accidental. This way, the clique structure of the network becomes more apparent.

  • In what ways is this new network a better representation of the social structure among the women? In what ways is it worse?

This new network is more likely to show the underlying social structure that these women are embedded in. However it makes certain women seem less connected than they actually are (e.g. is Miss Flora Price really completely isolated from the group, even having attended two events?). Moreover, the reduced network loses any sense of different strength of tie, so it erases the fact that, e.g., Mrs. Evelyn Jefferson is very tightly tied to Miss Theresa Anderson but less tightly tied to Miss Charlotte McDowd—both ties are coded simply as “present” in event_net_3plus.
